be.kuleuven.micas.signalStorage
Class CompressedNamesIndex

java.lang.Object
  be.kuleuven.micas.signalStorage.CompressedNamesIndex
All Implemented Interfaces:
MetaInfo, NamesIndex, java.io.Serializable
public class CompressedNamesIndex
extends java.lang.Object
implements NamesIndex, java.io.Serializable

a Header instance stores the names of the waves in a file, in the order in which their wave data is stored. You can use the methods from NamesIndex to access the names. The normal use of this header is to request signal indices by name, and to list all signal names that match a certain pattern. When writing a header-file-reader, you can use either *

  • CompressedNamesIndex( List compressedNames, List> sets )
  • CompressedNamesIndex( List flatNames )
To read a header from a file, use a separate reader file.
  • For HDR, @see ReaderHDR
  • Define similar classes for other header files
  • You can pass additional information between headerReader and bodyReader through the metaInfo
For debugging only , you can also use the following methods that provide access to the raw data getNumberOfRawSets() getRawSet( i ) getRawCompressedNames() printRawData() TODO: this class was not serializable. Is there a reason for this ? I don't think so

CompressedNamesIndex

public CompressedNamesIndex(java.util.List<java.lang.String> compressedNames,
                            java.util.List<java.util.List<java.lang.String>> sets)
create a SimulationHeader based on a list of compressed names and sets. Entries that end on #i are replaced with sets{i}.

Only forward references are allowed inside sets, e.g. entries in sets{3} can include #1, but entries in sets{1} cannot include #3

Parameters:
compressedNames - top-level names, potenially including #, and including units
sets - sets for substitution
